{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476252"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:43:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:43:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13708"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13708"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.03,0.45,0.22,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6327"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53987"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6327"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13708"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39458"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1464"},{"type":"tags","id":"2207"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11722"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14360"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14542"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14675"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15820"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16139"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53987"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-month-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his parent with a one-day history of vomiting and four episodes of diarrhoea. He has been feeding poorly and his last wet nappy was 12 hours ago. He has no significant medical history and is up to date with all immunisations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears lethargic with sunken eyes. His weight is 6 kg (10th percentile). His pulse rate is 180/min, blood pressure 70/40 mmHg, respiratory rate 50/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 35.5\u00b0C. Capillary blood glucose is 2.1 mmol/L (3.0-7.8).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diabetic ketoacidosis","Viral myocarditis","Accelerated starvation","Congenital adrenal hyperplasia","Intussusception"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant is showing signs of \u003Cstrong\u003Eaccelerated starvation\u003C/strong\u003E, a state of metabolic decompensation that can occur rapidly in young children due to their high metabolic rates and low glycogen stores compared to adults. The key diagnostic features are hypoglycemia, hypothermia, and dehydration, all of which are present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccelerated starvation remains the most likely diagnosis because it best explains the combination of symptoms and clinical findings. The rapid onset of vomiting and diarrhoea has likely led to poor oral intake, quickly depleting the infant\u0027s limited glycogen stores. This results in hypoglycemia (2.1 mmol/L), which is a hallmark of accelerated starvation. The hypothermia (35.5\u00b0C) is also consistent with this diagnosis, as the body\u0027s ability to maintain normal temperature is compromised in a state of metabolic stress. The dehydration, evidenced by sunken eyes and reduced urine output, further supports this diagnosis. The tachycardia and tachypnoea are likely compensatory responses to the metabolic acidosis that often accompanies accelerated starvation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic ketoacidosis\u003C/strong\u003E (DKA) is an important consideration in this case. DKA can present with vomiting, dehydration, and altered mental status in infants. However, DKA typically presents with hyperglycemia rather than hypoglycemia. The blood glucose of 2.1 mmol/L in this case is inconsistent with DKA. Additionally, DKA is uncommon in infants this young, and there is no mention of polyuria or polydipsia in the history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral myocarditis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with nonspecific symptoms such as lethargy, poor feeding, and tachypnoea in infants. However, it typically causes tachycardia out of proportion to fever, which is not present in this case. The hypoglycemia and hypothermia are also not typical features of myocarditis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital adrenal hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E (CAH) can present in infancy with hypoglycemia, dehydration and shock. However, this is less likely given the acute onset of symptoms and lack of virilization signs like ambiguous genitalia or hyperpigmentation that are often seen in CAH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntussusception\u003C/strong\u003E classically presents with a triad of intermittent abdominal pain, vomiting, and bloody \u0022currant jelly\u0022 stools. Lethargy can occur, but the other key features of accelerated starvation are not typical of intussusception.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Accelerated starvation occurs more rapidly in infants and young children compared to adults due to their higher metabolic rates and lower glycogen stores.","Key features of accelerated starvation include hypoglycemia, hypothermia, and dehydration.","Diabetic ketoacidosis in infants can present with vomiting, dehydration, and altered mental status, and should be considered in the differential diagnosis of a lethargic infant with metabolic derangement."],"references":["Millar R, Chiappazzo A, Palmer B. Starvation Ketosis in the Pediatric Emergency Department: A Prospective Estimate of Prevalence. Pediatr Emerg Care. 2022 Jan 1;38(1):e147-e150. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33170568/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39458"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13708"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39458"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-28T15:04:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-28T15:05:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6327"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53987"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"gr